{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd319966-b7bc-4a32-953e-7f557517ab7f","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform .NET diagnostics tool and requires no installation beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper OS-level analysis)\nIf you need kernel-level CPU stacks (drivers, GC, OS threads), use **PerfView** instead:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -ThreadTime -Duration:30\n```\n\n### Which to choose?\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Managed/.NET code hotspots, quick & lightweight |\n| `PerfView` | Full system analysis incl. kernel, GC, I/O stalls |\n\nFor a CPU-pegged .NET service, start with `dotnet-trace` — it's low-overhead and usually pinpoints the hot path fast.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"14182978-5ab6-4dd0-baf1-bba40031acfc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":396,"requestId":"6084:210779:209B5D:2A783C:69FFDEF0"},"id":"830f71a7-a758-4f47-ac82-6afcac3c651e","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:27:22.912Z","parentId":"00b20294-a5b0-49bb-836d-529a740bf4d0"}
